\parbox{3in}{The unit load is shown {\bf upwards} because that is the direction
assumed for $R_b$.}

\parbox{3in}{We must draw the displacement consistent
with the force. If $R_b$ acts {\bf upwards} on $b$, then the spring
must be in compression, therefore it must shorten, therefore
the displacement is {\bf downward}.}

\parbox{3in}{The displacement is shown upwards because we are going
to use the unit redundant to calculate it, and that will be shown upwards to
be consistent with the assumed direction of $R_b$. Thus, a +ive
displacement will be {\bf upwards}. This all makes the 
compatibility equations easier to get right $\ldots$}

\parbox{3in}{$-R_b/k$ is negative because it has to be downward for an upward 
value of $R_b$. $\Delta_{b0}$ and $f_{11}$ are positive upward because we have
assumed $R_b$ upward, and the unit force is chosen consistent
with that.}

Compatibility:
\noindent
\[
\begin{split}
-{R_b\over k} &= \Delta_{b0} + R_b f_{11}\\
-{R_b\over k} &= -{PL^3\over 48 EI} + R_b{L^3\over 48EI}\\
\therefore~R_b &= PL^3 {k\over kL^3 + 48EI}~~~~~(\therefore\uparrow)\\
\end{split}
\]
